    slug: "sayeda-khadija-ra-aur-unki-betiyan",
    description: `Sayeda Khadija (R.A) Aur Unki Betiyan is an Urdu-language biographical book that focuses on Sayeda Khadija bint Khuwaylid (may Allah be pleased with her) and her daughters from her marriage to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). While Khadija is widely known as the first wife of the Prophet and the first person to accept Islam, this book provides a more comprehensive and intimate look at her life as a mother and the lives of the children she raised — particularly her daughters Zainab, Ruqayyah, Umm Kulthum, and Fatimah az-Zahra. This maternal and familial perspective on Khadija's life offers readers a dimension that is often underrepresented in general biographical works, which tend to focus primarily on her role as a successful businesswoman and the Prophet's supportive wife.

The book begins with Khadija's background — her noble lineage among the Quraysh, her marriages before Islam (she was married twice before Prophet Muhammad), her successful trading business that made her one of the wealthiest women in Makkah, and the qualities that earned her the titles "Khadija al-Kubra" (Khadija the Great) and "Ameerat Quraysh" (Princess of Quraysh). The narrative then explores her marriage to Prophet Muhammad before his prophethood, describing the trust and mutual respect that characterized their relationship — including the remarkable fact that Khadija, a wealthy and established businesswoman, proposed marriage to Muhammad, who was then a young man of modest means known for his honesty and trustworthiness. This section highlights Khadija's independence, wisdom, and ability to recognize true worth beyond material considerations.

The core of the book is dedicated to the lives of Khadija's daughters. Each daughter's life is presented with attention to her unique personality, her role in the early Muslim community, and the trials she faced. Zainab, the eldest, and her migration to Madinah, her marriage to Abu al-As, and her patience during his captivity; Ruqayyah and her migration to Abyssinia and then Madinah, her marriage to Uthman ibn Affan, and her death at the time of the Battle of Badr; Umm Kulthum, who also married Uthman after Ruqayyah's passing; and the most detailed section on Fatimah az-Zahra, the youngest daughter, who was deeply devoted to her father the Prophet and who became the mother of the Prophet's grandchildren, Hasan and Husayn. The book draws on authentic hadith sources for its information, ensuring historical reliability. The Urdu prose is accessible and engaging, making this book suitable for women's study circles, Islamic school curricula, and individual readers who want to understand the personal and familial dimensions of these important figures from Islamic history.`,
